On Tue, Jan 19, 2010 at 7:37 AM, Mike Kelly &lt;mike@...&gt; wrote:

&gt; Essentially just the amount of clients that understand the media type.
&gt;
&gt; I tend to look at it in terms of concentration/dilution - i.e. custom media
&gt; types are more &#39;concentrated&#39;, in that they have stronger meaning but to a
&gt; smaller spread of clients. An equally generic media types are more dilute,
&gt; in that they have weaker meaning but to a larger spread of clients.
&gt;
&gt; Where you draw the line should depend on how wide a particular application
&gt; is intended to be distributed - extending atom is an example of a good
&gt; opportunity for compromise.
&gt;
&gt; - Mike
&gt;

Ok, I buy that more clients will &quot;accept&quot; (potentially) the media type, but
that doesn&#39;t really mean they understand it (from a &quot;get stuff done&quot;
perspective), if the media type has been extended to now include semantics
not defined into the original specification of the media type.  The client
will just see junk.  Maybe &quot;reach&quot; is the wrong word to define what we&#39;re
trying to describe here because I find it very misleading (personally).

